s shapes modern slavery. And he asks how we can study and measure this mostly hidden crime. Throughout, Bales emphasizes that to end global slavery, we must first understand it. This book is a step in that direction.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aForced labor. 0aProstitution. 0aSlave labor. 0aSlave trade. 0aSlavery. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh  aabolition.  aacademic.  aantislavery.  acrime.  acriminal justice.  acurrent affairs.  aeconomics.  aeconomy.  aethics.  aexpose.  aglobal economy.  aglobal issues.  aglobal slavery.  aglobalization.  ahuman rights.  ahuman trafficking.  ainternational.  amodern slavery.  amorals.  apakistan.  aphenomenon.  apolitics.  arace issues.  arace.  aracism.  aredemption.  ascholarly.  aservitude.  aslavery.  athailand.  atrue story.  aus history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093207440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520932074423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520932074/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles